poem:
The Desiring-Path

'Twas brillig, and the desiring-path did gyre and gimble in the wold;
All mimsy were the footprints, and the hedges spang-boing gold;
One-short-way, sly-whig, with zig-zag zip and sigh so near;
Desire maps the land with longing in the ear;
The path slithers on—twistly-twirl through grass and time unrolled;
And every tread leaves a tale of want, both shy and bold.

The Music-Room Jabberwocky

'Twas brillig in the music-room, and the clefs did slithy-sway;
The piano-owl hooted a moonlit tune in a whisker of bright day.
Bow-bats of the violins dipped and danced in twirl and twine;
While the metronome-wisp tick-tocked in rhyme with the timpani's chime.

A chorus of chairs creaked-bleak with a lullaby-sneeze and sigh;
The drum-kettle sputtered spice, and the horn-nests hummed nearby.
Note-squirrels zipped through air, catching timbres by the tail;
And every shelf-peg winked in the candle-flower pale.

Beware the Discordoodle and the mute-Cacophony-Creep,
They gnaw the velvet hush where lullabies sleep.
One snicker-crack of treble-tangle, one bow of low C-blue;
The room exhales a crescendo, and sighs, "We belong to you."

So tiptoe through the pedals and the shelves of sound;
Let music roam like a sprightly swarm around.

The Awl-Wock in the Woven Wabe

Twas glintish, and the awl-wock woke in the woven wabe;
With zip-zop zing of steel it pricked the cloth and whispered seam.
The bobbins blinkle-blooped, the threadlings sang in threadish glee;
While needle-nymphs stitched moonlight into raveled dreams with gleam.

The awl-wock bent its bright-tipped beak, a speck of tempered light;
It carved out tiny moon-holes in the darkening night.
Snik! went the shears, a chorus clack and cheer;
And hems aligned themselves, as if they knew the pier.

Frabjous day! The seam lay straight as sunlit line;
The awl-wock bowed to the loom and melted into the twine.

The Film-Camera Jabberwock

’Twas glimmering, and the film-cams did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All flimsy were the sprockets, and the emulsion outgrabe.
Beware the Shutterwock, my son! The jaws that bite, the clips that snare;
Beware the Jubjub of halation, and the frumious frame-clip glare!

He clutched his lens-hood tight, long time the ISO-light he sought;
Then, with a flick of aperture, summoned daylight from the dark.

One, two! The frame-doors clacked; three, four! The negatives sang;
Five! The grain danced merrily, and the shadows twang.
Six! The exposure balanced, the highlights purred bright;
Seven! The film rolled on, a ribbon of silver light.

O frabjous day! Callooh! Callay!
He snapped the shutter with a jubilant zing;
And the Jabberwock, with film in tow, did vanish into the light he brought to play.

The lab-lights winked as the reels began to unwind,
And the world condensed to frames of grain and gleam;
Thus spoke the camera, patient and kind:
Record the dawn, remember the dream, and seize the beam.

The Printerjam Jabberwock

’Twas brillig, and the feed did slork and zing;
All mimsy were the papers in the tray;
The toner-tangles twimble, the nibble-nocks clang,
And the jamblewock lurked in the cable-way.

“Beware the Jamberwock, my child!
The jaws that click, the gears that bite;
He comes with a whirr and a slippery smile,
And leaves behind a blot of smeary night.”

One, two! One, two! And through the shop it went,
The sprocket-squeaks sang, the carriage hummed;
Till with a snap the jam lay rent,
And the page emerged, crisp as dawn, unmummed.

The Map-Wyrd

'Twas mapish, and the gridlines slithered wide;
Contour-sprites twined in a murmur-braid;
Latitudes winked softly in a seam of light,
While legends hummed along the margin's shade.

Beware the Path-Wock with its grin of ink;
Its routes gnaw borders and make the borders blink;
One, two! One, two! the compass chimes in spin,
As coastlines twist and twirl in moonlit din.

O frabjous scale! O beamish legend-bells!
The meridians march in lilting, backhand dwells;
A map-sprite giggles from the vellum fold,
And every coast yawns wide to welcome bold.

So fold the world with careful, careless grace;
Let margins bloom and ink-run rivers race;
For in this graphed-up dream of land and sea,
The map becomes the door to what will be.

The Music-Room Jabberwock

'Twas brillig, and the metronomes did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the pianos, and the keys outgrabe in the stave.
Beware the Jabber-notes, my child! The chords that bite, the rests that gleam;
The vorpal frets did snicker-snack through the dusky beam.
One, two! One, two! The bass-hums thump a merry rhyme;
While violins twirl glissando through the seam of time.
He took his timbre-mallet in hand; long time the room he scanned;
Till the ceiling hummed a lullaby and lamps grew bright and grand.
"'Twas brillig, and the chairs did wriggle in the night;
The rug did jiggle-jump, and dust motes danced in light."
And hast thou slain the Jabbernote? O frabjous day! Callooh! Callay!
The music-room sighed a chorus, and dawn spilled in to play.

Déjà Vu in the Wabe

'Twas déjà vu, and the wabe-wind snick-snackled the brain;
The slithy memory-moths gyred and gimble’d time again.
Borogoves whispered frabjous loops, as doors relatch their skeins;
Mimsy echoes drift along the same familiar lanes.
In gloam, the moment re-snapped with velvet, well-worn grace;
The clock-clatterers tick backward through a mirrored space.
Vorpal thoughts pricked once, then lolled to the old refrain;
We wander through a corridor that time forgot to name.
Snick-snack goes the heart, then sighs, “I’ve seen this before,”
Yet every page is printed new on the same old door.
Chortle-bells clink, and memory-lamps flare, then fade;
Déjà vu grins, and the tale repeats—in each passing shade.

Wingfolds at the Backstage Gate

'Twas glimmerish, and the wingfolds did gyre and gleam;
Back-stage murmurs curled like velvet smoke;
The cue-bells popped in soft, shy steam,
And shadow-lace draped every timber yoke.

Two seam-sprites whispered in a seam-woven tongue:
"Step through the hinge between light and shade;";
Where light-drops spill and quiet bells are sung,
And tinsled moths in lantern-gloom parade.

The wing-doors sigh-snerk with a copper kiss,
The skirts of night unfold in pocket-sky;
A chorus of hush-buzz and soft-hand bliss
Glints on the wings like stars that never die.

The wings retreat; the stage heart drums in time;
And curtains wait to bloom with another rhyme.

Interference in the Wavetangle
Twas brillig, and the fringe-waves flurried on the glassy sea of sound;
Two sly-sine sprites, sip-snap and slithy, met where the crests were crowned.
They murmur in portmanteau twine—construktive, destruktive, in a gleaming chord;
When phase and crest align, they leap to peak-bloom, bright as a starward ward.
When crest meets trough, the glow curls back and fades—destructive, dim and thin;
An empty hush slides over the tide, and echoes sigh within.
The wavetangle hums with a beamy-babble, fizz-wobble, twink-dish of light;
Tulgey shadows twirl with phase-lace, weaving day from night.
Thus interference prances in jabberwocky tune across the air;
Waves kiss and clash and conspire to brighten or dim, as if by careful dare.

The Creep in the Wabe

'Twas creepish, and the slithy toves did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the borl-creeps, and the frumious shadows swale.
"Beware the Creep, my friend!" the mome-glee cried in gloom;
"For he will nibble at your courage and slip away at bloom."

He bore his gleam-dart in hand; long time the foe he sought to quell;
And through the gloam there hissed a whisper-wisp, the Creep with stealthy spell.

One, two! One, two! and through and through
The Creep did glint and snicker-snack the night in blue.

The air grew thin with gnarl-breeze and drearish sighs of night;
Till dawn awoke and shadow-mirth melted into light.

The Awl-Wand in the Wabe

In frabjous gloam the awl woke with a zing;
Its prong did gimble where the threads did cling;
It whibble-wobbled along the warp and weft;
And stitched the night with a keen-sparkle heft.

The cloth-nymphs hummed snick-snack through hem and seam;
While zizzle-paths unfurled within the dreamer’s dream;
It wheeled on the loom, a silver-sprock of night;
And every stitch became a star-lace light.

Owl-skirl whispered: pierce, but keep it kind;
The awl replied with a bristle-bright mind;
It carved a map of pockets in the dusk;
And threaded dawn through every careful husk.

So heed the awl, ye sewers brave and true;
For holes are doors to mornings made anew;
Though sharp its bite, its rhythm is soft and warm;
The awl will wake the fabric's waking form.

The Science-Fair Jabberwock
Twas brillig in the science-hall, where lanterns fizz and glow;
Slithy goggles glimmered, diodes winked to and fro.
Mimsy booths did gimble with beakers, fizzing bright and wild;
Borogoves of student-scholars tinkered every child.

A glow-pot whipped a moonbeam, then bubbled into dawn;
A robo-tarriff clacked its gears with a tinkling yawn.
The data-gyre spun snick-snick numbers in the air;
While chalk and solder sang a frabjous, hopeful prayer.

"Beware the rubric-wock, my dear," the judges cried in glee;
"Present your methods clearly, and show your work for all to see."
They scribbled scores on parchment, snick-snack and neat;
And every small inventor bowed before the crowd's warm beat.

Then gyre and gimble through the beaming crowds they went;
The fair grew brighter with each quirk and invention bent.
The hall exhaled a sigh of joy, a curious, bright perfume;
For science, at its tinkering heart, found room for every bloom.

Morning Fog, Jabberwocky-Style

'Twas mornish, and the fog did gyre and gimble in the gloam;
Slithy wisps slunk through hedges, mimsy and froth with foam;
Brillig dew dripped from eaves on a sleepy pane,
While borogoves bobbled by in a muffled mossy train;
O frabjous day! Callooh! Callay! the dawn did sigh,
As sun-schooled beams wore pastel halos in the sky;
The foghorn murmured muffles of morning’s tune,
And all the world wore velvet gray till the noon.

The Music-Room, Jabberwocky-Style

'Twas brillig, and the metronomes did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
The chairs were mimsy, velvet rugs did slither-sway and stave.
The piano-lids yawned wide and breathed a moonlit octave through;
The violins winked and wobbled; the cello hummed a sleepy blue.

A tuning-fork blinked, sugar-spark, and clefs sang soft and sly;
Cymbal-snaps clacked out zig-zag prayers to the listening sky.
Stand-bow whispered, "snicker-snack," as clock-dial teeth kept time;
While every key awoke, and laughed in color-spark and rhyme.

From door to curtain, borogoves of echo drift and dive;
The room swells with frabjous rumor, alive with jingle and jive.
The music-room cradles silence like a nest of silver thyme,
And yawns into morning with a soft, bright, lasting chime.

Desire-Path in the Wabe

Twas brillig, and the wabe did slither with desire;
Desire-paths glimmered through grass and dust and time;
Slithy footprints giggled, gimble-flecked with fire,
While longing-bands woven in their ears kept rhyme.

Mimsy the lanes of will made bow and bend;
Grimble-grass curled up to greet the feet;
The path, alive with want, would whisper, "Descend—
Each worn rut tells a choice you must complete."

One track, then another, thrimble-turn and slip;
The world-tracks flutter in the hush of gloam;
And every tread designs the line you grip—
A map of who you are when you are home.

Follow, and be led by what you yearn to be;
Desire-paths bloom where hearts refuse to flee.

The Shutterwock of the Film-Reel

'Twas brillig, and the lens-lamps did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the emulsions, borogoves outgrabe.
"Beware the Shutterwock, my dear, the jaws that bite and the frames that snare;
The light that nips the night and leaves but a captured glare."

One, two, three—the frame-wheels whirr and sigh;
The film unspools a midnight lullaby.
The aperture yawns; the viewfinder croons in chime;
And grain and glow entwine in the margins of time.

O frabjous day! Callooh! Callay! The negative wakes to light;
A silver dawn is hammered from the diurnal night.
And so the camera's curious engine hums its cryptic tune,
A Jabberwock in metal and glass, singing to the moon.
